higakun, I'm not sure I follow why that's unfair.  If you have a better suggestion of how people should be taxed, I would like to hear it.  The way I see it, there's 2 general ways it could go down for a flat tax (which has always been based on income).<br>
<br>
1)  every person pays X AMOUNT.<br>
<br>
now, let's say that was $5000 per person.  Well, that means the wealthy guy with $1000000 would be paying a small amount compared to what he makes.  Ok, fine.<br>
<br>
but, what about the middle class or poor?  What if they only make about $20000 per year, which is common?  That means, they're having to pay 25% of their income every year just in taxes.<br>
<br>
A flat amount like that doesn't work and isn't fair to the poor.<br>
<br>
2) every person pays X PERCENTAGE.<br>
<br>
ok, this time let's say it's 5% of a person's income.  Now, the poor man that makes $20,000 only pays about $1000 of his income each year.  The rich guy pays about $10,000.  I don't see why this is really unfair considering the rich guy still ends up with considerably more money.<br>
<br>
The rich SHOULD pay more.  It's not punishment, it's merely the fact that taxes have always been based off income.  I also think you need to step back and consider the definition of greed since in your scenario, it's the rich that are greedy, not the poor.<br>
<br>
There are some alternatives, like the sliding scale and tax brackets, but it still requires the rich to pay slightly more than the poor.<br>
  <br>
<br>
